@node DiskMon
@next DiskMon
@prev DiskMon
With the DiskMonitor you can view and edit the blocks of a disk.


@{FG Highlight}Gadgets@{FG Text}:

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Read@{FG Text}@{BG Background}
DiksMon reads and displays the selected block of the selected Drive.

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Checksum@{FG Text}@{BG Background}
DiskMon calculates the checksum of the displayed block if the block type is
 - Root Block
 - Directory
 - File Header
 - File List
 - Boot Block (only if 'Check' is 'on')
 - old filesystem Data Block
 - Directory Cache Block
 - Hard Link
 - Soft Link
 - Rigid-Disk-Blocks (RDSK,PART,FSHD,LSEG,BADB,...)
Only use it if the block type is not '?? Unknown ??'.

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Write@{FG Text}@{BG Background}
DiskMon writes the block to the selected block number and drive.
Remember to correct the checksum if required.

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Edit@{FG Text}@{BG Background}
Selects the mode of editing. HEX means you have to enter the data as
hexadecimal (half-)bytes, ASCII for entering characters.

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Search@{FG Text}@{BG Background}
A requester is displayed where you can select the startblock, endblock
and the text you whish to search. 'Stop' aborts while 'Search' starts
searching. If the text is found you can 'Stop' searching or continue
searching by clicking 'Search' again.
Search is case sensitive and no patterns are used.
If you want to search hexadecimal data you can do this by entering
'$' as the fist character (for example '$AB cd 12' which is equal to
'$ abc d12' but ' $AbcD12' is wrong because of the space before the '$').

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Header@{FG Text}@{BG Background}
Search a fileheader on the selected disk.
Select the file-/dirname in the asl-requester and the fileheader of this
file/dir will be loaded and displayed.
ATTENTION: The file has to be on the selected drive, else you get the wrong
           block or an error.
If you don't have the 'asl.library', you have to enter the full path and
filename in the requester.

@{FG FillText}@{BG Fill}Repair@{FG Text}@{BG Background} (ONLY Floppy Disks)
If there is a read/write error on the disk you can't read the whole track,
but in most cases there is only one of the 11/22 blocks destroyed. Diskmon
reads the selected track and tries to recover as much data as possible. It
will be displayed which block is ok ('repaired') and which block could not
be corrected ('not repaired'). Now you are asked if you want to write the
data back to disk or not. You may change the disk to write the reults to
another disk. If you select 'Yes' the recovered data is written to the disk,
'No' aborts.
ATTENTION !!! if you write the data back to the same disk and there are
blocks which are not repaired, there is no chance of getting lost data back.

