@node "MFM Read"
@toc mfmed
Reads a track from disk.
@endnode

@node "MFM Write"
@toc mfmed
Writes the track back to disk.
@endnode

@node "MFM IndexSync"
@toc mfmed
Toogles the indexsync mode. AmigaDOS does not use indexsync but PC-DOS does.
@endnode

@node "MFM TrackInfo"
@toc memed
Displays some informations about the track (format, checksumms, etc.).
@endnode

@node "MFM WriteLen"
@toc mfmed
Number of bytes (decimal) to write to the disk. On 880KB disks, AmigaDOS
uses 11968 bytes of data (11*1088) and the rest of about 700 bytes are the
gap.
@endnode

@node "MFM PreWrite"
@toc mfmed
Number of bytes (decimal) to write before the real data. These bytes are
0xAA which is decoded 0x00. PreWrite is used to delete possible syncs in the
gap because the real data is less than would fit on the disk. PreWrite is
not used if IndexSync is on.
@endnode

@node "MFM Cyl."
@toc mfmed
Number of the Cylinder to read/write.
@endnode

@node "MFM Head"
@toc mfmed
Select head 0 or 1.
@endnode

@node "MFM Arrange SN"
@toc mfmed
The sectors are arranged by the sector number. This means at offset 0 will
be sector 0, offset 1088 sector 1, ..., offset 10880 sector 10.
@endnode

@node "MFM Arrange SO"
@toc mfmed
The sectors are arranged by the sector offset like they are written to the
disk by AmigaDOS. In the error-line (right last line below the gadgets) it
is displayed in which order the sectors are arranged, '-' means sector not
found. Additionaly the gap is arranged after the last sector.
@endnode

@node "MFM Sync"
@toc mfmed
DiskMonTools searches the given SYNC-word and if found the data will be
arranged, that the SYNC-word is at offset 0.
@endnode

@node "MFM Find"
@toc mfmed
Searches the giver word. If found, a requester appears
where you can continue searching or stop searching.
@endnode

@node "MFM Sync,Find"
@toc mfmed
Enter the word to find/sync.
@endnode

@node "MFM Scroll Data"
@toc mfmed
Cycles the data 1,2,4 bit or a given number of bytes left or right.
@endnode

@node "MFM Quit"
@toc mfmed
Returns to main menu.
@endnode

